    <section class="faq">
      <h2>Extreme FAQ: Real Estate Edition</h2>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I set up a dispensary in a converted garage?</summary>
        <p>Maybe, but it's complicated. The property must meet all commercial building codes, OCP security requirements, and local zoning. A converted garage can work if it's structurally sound, meets ADA accessibility requirements, has proper ventilation, and your municipality approves it. Many operators find new construction or purpose-built spaces are actually easier to permit.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Do I need special zoning for a drive-through window?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Drive-through windows require specific zoning approvals that often aren't permitted for cannabis dispensaries in Maine. Some municipalities have banned them entirely due to concerns about youth access and traffic. Even where allowed, you'll need additional parking, a dedicated drive-through lane, and local planning board approval.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>How far must my dispensary be from a school?</summary>
        <p>Maine law requires adult-use cannabis retailers to be at least 500 feet from a school (public or private, K-12). However, some municipalities have imposed stricter distance requirements—some up to 1,000 feet. Always check both state law AND local ordinances before finalizing a location.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I lease space in a building that has apartments above?</summary>
        <p>It depends on local zoning and building codes. Many municipalities require complete separation between commercial cannabis operations and residential spaces—meaning separate entrances, separate ventilation systems, and no shared access. Some towns allow vertical mixed-use with strict separation requirements. Check with your local planning office early in your search.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What happens if my lease is up and the landlord won't renew?</summary>
        <p>This is why long-term leases (5-10 years) with renewal options are critical. If you're month-to-month or have a short lease, you risk losing your location and your license. Maine requires OCP notification of any location change, and relocating triggers a new facility inspection. Plan for stability from day one.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I operate out of my home initially?</summary>
        <p>No. Maine regulations require dispensaries to operate in commercial zoned properties. Home-based cannabis businesses are not permitted for retail operations. Even cultivation for personal use has strict limits. Keep your business operations completely separate from any residential property.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Do I need a backup location in my application?</summary>
        <p>OCP doesn't require a backup location, but having one can strengthen your application. It shows planning and reduces concerns about whether you can actually open. Many applicants list their primary location and note that alternative sites have been identified if needed.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What about properties with environmental issues?</summary>
        <p>Be very careful with properties that have environmental contamination history (old gas stations, industrial sites, etc.). You'll need Phase I and potentially Phase II environmental assessments, and remediation can be expensive. Also check with your municipality—some have banned dispensaries from former contaminated sites.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can my landlord prohibit cannabis in the lease even if the town allows it?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Even in cannabis-friendly towns, individual landlords can prohibit cannabis businesses in their leases. Always ask landlords directly about their cannabis policy before spending time on a location.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What's more important: location or cost?</summary>
        <p>Location. A great location in a compliant zone with good traffic is worth paying premium rent. A cheap location in a questionable zone is a money pit. When in doubt, prioritize location quality over cost savings.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

